Cloud computing provides IT resources on-demand over the 
Internet at pay-as-you-go prices. Cloud providers like 
Amazon Web Services offer computing power, storage, and 
databases on an as-needed basis instead of buying, 
operating, and maintaining physical data centers and servers.

Why cloud computing matters: 
Cost efficiency: Cloud computing eliminates the need for upfront investment in physical infrastructure.
Pay-as-you-go models ensure businesses only pay for the resources they use.
Reduces operational and maintenance costs associated with traditional on-premises solutions.

Scalability: Allows businesses to scale computing resources up or down based on demand.
Enables flexibility in adjusting resources to accommodate fluctuating workloads.
Avoids the need for over-provisioning and ensures optimal resource utilization.

Accessibility: Cloud computing Provides global accessibility to applications and data via the internet.
Facilitates remote access, supporting the growing trend of remote work.
Enhances collaboration among geographically dispersed teams.

Flexibility: It offers a range of service models (IaaS, PaaS, Saas) to suit specific business needs. 
Allows customization and integration of various cloud services to create tailored solutions.
Enables rapid deployment of applications and services.

Innovation: Provides access to cutting-edge technologies including AO, machine learning, and IoT.
Accelerates time-to-market for new products and services.
Supports experimentation and development of innovative solutions without significant upfront investment. 
